        "content": "Install your data analyst toolbox and understand what it means to think like a data analyst — no math degree required.\n\nA data analyst is like a detective for a company. Imagine you own a small coffee shop. You have piles of receipts, customer feedback forms, and inventory sheets. Somewhere in that pile is the answer to: Why did our sales drop last Tuesday? A data analyst digs through the mess, finds the pattern, and says: It's because we ran out of oat milk — 40% of our customers order oat lattes.\n\nYou don't need to be a genius. You need to be curious, patient, and methodical.\n\nPicture this: Maria is a new junior analyst at an online clothing store. Her manager asks which products to discount this month.\nMaria doesn't guess. She follows the data step by step:\n\n1. Opens the sales spreadsheet\n2. Notices winter jackets have 500 units in stock but only sold 20 last week\n3. Checks the weather forecast — it's warming up next week\n4. Recommends a 30% discount on jackets\nResult: Jackets sell out, the store makes $15,000 instead of sitting on dead inventory.\n\n## Your Toolbox — Install Today\n\n1. **VS Code** — Your writing desk. Download from https://code.visualstudio.com\n2. **Node.js** — The engine that runs code. Download from https://nodejs.org (get the LTS version).\n3. **Git** — Your undo button. Download from https://git-scm.com\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhich version of Node.js should you install?\nA) The newest Current version\nB) The LTS (Long Term Support) version\nC) Any version works\nD) You don't need Node.js\nCorrect: B\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhat does Git do?\nA) It's a programming language\nB) It tracks changes to your files so you can undo mistakes\nC) It runs JavaScript code\nD) It creates spreadsheets\nCorrect: B\n\nDownloading from the wrong place. Always go to the official website. Check the URL.\n\n- A data analyst finds patterns in data to help businesses make decisions\n- You need curiosity, not a math degree\n- Today we installed: VS Code, Node.js, Git",
