        "type": "practice",
        "duration": "45-60 mins",
        "content": "The first step in any BI tool is connecting to your data source.\n\n**Common data sources:**\n- Databases (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, MySQL)\n- Files (Excel, CSV, JSON)\n- Cloud services (Google Analytics, Salesforce, Azure)\n- Web APIs\n\n**In Power BI — Get Data:**\n1. Click 'Get Data' → choose source type\n2. Enter connection details (server, database, file path)\n3. Preview the data\n4. Click 'Load' or 'Transform Data'\n\n**In Tableau — Connect:**\n1. Click 'Connect to Data' → choose source\n2. Drag tables onto the canvas\n3. Define relationships between tables\n\n**Best practice:** Always do a quick data check after connecting — verify row counts, column names, and data types.\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhat's the first step in building a BI dashboard?\nA) Create a chart\nB) Connect to a data source\nC) Format colors\nD) Share with stakeholders\nCorrect: B\n\n## Power Query (PL-300 Exam Topic)\n\n**Power Query** is Power BI's data transformation tool. It connects to data sources and lets you clean/reshape data before loading into your model.\n\n**Key Power Query operations:**\n- **Promote headers** — use first row as column names\n- **Change type** — set columns to text, number, date\n- **Remove columns** — drop unnecessary fields\n- **Split column** — separate full names into first/last\n- **Merge queries** — join tables (like SQL JOINs)\n- **Append queries** — stack tables (like SQL UNION)\n- **Pivot/Unpivot** — reshape data\n- **Replace values** — fix inconsistencies\n- **Filter rows** — keep only relevant data\n\n**PL-300 tip:** Power Query (M language) is tested on the exam. Focus on understanding transformation steps and the query editor interface.\n",
        "quiz": [
          {
            "question": "First step in building a BI dashboard?",
            "options": [
              "Create chart",
              "Connect to data source",
              "Format colors",
              "Share"
            ],
            "correctAnswerIndex": 1
          },
          { "question": "Interview: You connect to a CSV and the data types are all wrong. How do you fix it in Power Query?", "options": ["Manually retype every cell", "Use the 'Change Type' step in Power Query Editor to set each column's data type before loading", "Ignore it and load anyway", "Delete the CSV"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: What's the difference between merging and appending queries in Power Query?", "options": ["They are the same", "Merging joins columns from two tables (like SQL JOIN), appending stacks rows (like SQL UNION)", "Merging stacks rows, appending joins columns", "Neither is useful"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: When connecting to a SQL database for BI, why might you use a SQL query instead of importing the whole table?", "options": ["SQL queries are slower", "To reduce data size by filtering and aggregating at the source, improving performance and reducing load", "You should always import whole tables", "SQL doesn't support filtering"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: Explain what 'Promote Headers' does and why it matters.", "options": ["It deletes the first row", "It uses the first row of data as column names instead of generic names like Column1, Column2", "It highlights headers", "It sorts the data"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "w18-d3",
        "title": "Day 3: Data Modeling in BI",
        "description": "Design star schemas with fact and dimension tables",
        "type": "learn",
        "duration": "45-60 mins",
        "content": "**Data modeling** in BI means defining how your tables relate to each other — like setting up foreign keys in a database.\n\n**Star schema — the standard BI model:**\n- **Fact table** — the central table with measurable data (sales, orders, transactions)\n- **Dimension tables** — descriptive data around the facts (customers, products, dates)\n\n```\n    customers ─── sales ─── products\n                      │\n                    dates\n```\n\n**In Power BI — Model view:**\n- Drag and drop to connect tables\n- Define relationships (one-to-many, many-to-many)\n- Set cross-filter direction\n\nA good data model makes building reports much easier. A bad model makes everything harder.\n\n## Row-Level Security (RLS) — PL-300 Exam Topic\n\n**RLS** restricts which data a user can see based on their identity. For example, a regional manager should only see their region's sales.\n\n**In Power BI:**\n```\n-- DAX-based RLS rule for the Sales table\n[Region] = USERPRINCIPALNAME()\n```\nThis filter is applied automatically — the user never knows other regions exist.\n\n**RLS vs. report-level filters:**\n- Report filters are optional (users can remove them)\n- RLS is mandatory (applied at the data source level)\n- RLS applies to ALL reports using the dataset\n\n**PL-300 Exam Tip:** Know how to set up RLS using DAX filter expressions and how to test RLS with the 'View As' feature in Power BI Desktop.\n\n## Data Security in BI\n- **OLS (Object-Level Security)** — hide entire tables or columns from certain users\n- **Shared datasets** — publish once, secure centrally\n- **Workspace roles** — Viewer, Contributor, Member, Admin\n\nData security is not just a technical concern — it's a governance requirement (GDPR, HIPAA).\n\n:::checkpoint\nIn a star schema, what's the fact table?\nA) A table with descriptive attributes\nB) The central table with measurable data\nC) A table of dates\nD) A table with formatting rules\nCorrect: B",
        "quiz": [
          {
            "question": "In star schema, the fact table is?",
            "options": [
              "Descriptive attributes",
              "Central measurable data",
              "Date table",
              "Formatting rules"
            ],
            "correctAnswerIndex": 1
          },
          { "question": "Interview: Explain the difference between a fact table and a dimension table with an example.", "options": ["They are identical", "Fact table stores measures like sales amount (e.g., each row is a transaction), dimension table stores attributes like customer name or product category", "Fact table stores names, dimension stores numbers", "Dimension tables are always smaller"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: What is row-level security and when would you use it in a BI report?", "options": ["It hides all data", "RLS restricts data access so each user only sees their own region's data, used when different stakeholders should see different subsets", "It secures the file with a password", "It's the same as report-level filters"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: Why is a star schema preferred over a normalized schema in BI?", "options": ["It uses less storage", "Star schemas are optimized for read/query performance with fewer joins, making reports faster", "Normalized schemas can't be used in BI", "There is no difference"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: How would you model a many-to-many relationship between products and sales in a star schema?", "options": ["You can't model many-to-many", "Use a bridge table or create a composite key; most BI tools can handle many-to-many with proper configuration", "Flatten all data into one table", "Use two separate fact tables"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "w18-d4",
        "title": "Day 4: Calculated Columns",
        "description": "Create new columns with formulas in BI tools",
        "type": "practice",
        "duration": "45-60 mins",
        "content": "**Calculated columns** are new columns you create in your BI tool using formulas — like adding a column in Excel.\n\n**In Power BI (DAX):**\n```\nProfit = Sales[Revenue] - Sales[Cost]\n```\n\n**In Tableau (Calculated Fields):**\n```\nProfit = [Revenue] - [Cost]\n```\n\n**Common calculated columns:**\n- Profit = Revenue - Cost\n- Age = DATEDIFF(birth_date, TODAY(), YEAR)\n- Category = IF [Amount] > 1000 THEN 'High' ELSE 'Low'\n- Full Name = [First Name] & ' ' & [Last Name]\n\n**Calculated columns vs. measures:**\n- Calculated columns = row-by-row (like a new column in a table)\n- Measures = aggregate (like SUM, AVERAGE for the whole report)\n\nStart with calculated columns; they're more intuitive.\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhat's a calculated column in BI?\nA) A column imported from a database\nB) A new column created with a formula\nC) A chart type\nD) A filter\nCorrect: B",
        "quiz": [
          {
            "question": "What's a calculated column?",
            "options": [
              "Imported column",
              "New column created with formula",
              "Chart type",
              "Filter"
            ],
            "correctAnswerIndex": 1
          },
          { "question": "Interview: What's the difference between a calculated column and a measure in Power BI?", "options": ["They are the same thing", "A calculated column evaluates row-by-row and stores values in memory, while a measure is evaluated at query time based on filter context", "Measures are slower", "Calculated columns don't use RAM"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: When would a calculated column be a bad choice compared to doing the calculation in the source query?", "options": ["Calculated columns are always best", "When the data is large and the calculation can be done more efficiently in SQL before loading into Power BI", "Source queries can't do calculations", "There's no difference in performance"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: In Tableau, how is a calculated field different from a Power BI calculated column?", "options": ["They are identical in every way", "Tableau calculated fields can be either row-level or aggregate, similar to both calculated columns and measures in Power BI", "Tableau doesn't have calculated fields", "Power BI doesn't have calculated columns"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: Write a calculated column formula that categorizes sales as 'High', 'Medium', or 'Low' based on thresholds.", "options": ["=IF(Sales>1000,'High','Low')", "=IF(Sales>1000,'High',IF(Sales>500,'Medium','Low'))", "=CATEGORIZE(Sales)", "=SWITCH(Sales,1000,'High',500,'Medium','Low')"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "w18-d5",
        "title": "Day 5: Mini-Project: First Report",
        "description": "Build a simple BI report with charts and filters",
