      {
        "id": "w19-d1",
        "title": "Day 1: DAX Basics",
        "description": "Learn Power BI's formula language for measures",
        "type": "learn",
        "duration": "45-60 mins",
        "content": "**DAX (Data Analysis Expressions)** is Power BI's formula language. It's similar to Excel formulas but works with tables and filters.\n\n**Basic DAX measures:**\n```\nTotal Sales = SUM(Sales[Amount])\nAverage Sale = AVERAGE(Sales[Amount])\nNumber of Orders = COUNTROWS(Sales)\n```\n\n**FILTER context — DAX calculates in context:**\nIf you put 'Total Sales' next to a product name, DAX automatically sums only that product's sales. This is called filter context.\n\n**CALCULATE — change the filter context:**\n```\nHigh Value Sales = CALCULATE(SUM(Sales[Amount]), Sales[Amount] > 1000)\n```\n\nDAX can be tricky at first. Start with simple SUM and COUNT measures, then gradually explore CALCULATE.\n\n**PL-300 Exam Tip:** The exam heavily tests CALCULATE filter context, time intelligence (SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR, TOTALYTD), and iterator functions (SUMX, AVERAGEX). Practice writing measures that change filter context.\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhat is DAX used for?\nA) Cleaning data\nB) Writing formulas in Power BI\nC) Connecting to databases\nD) Creating charts\nCorrect: B\n\n:::checkpoint\n(PL-300 Style) What does CALCULATE(SUM(Sales[Amount]), Sales[Region] = \"West\") do?\nA) Sums all sales\nB) Sums sales only for the West region by modifying filter context\nC) Filters the table permanently\nD) Creates a new column\nCorrect: B\n\n## Time Intelligence in DAX (PL-300 Exam Topic)\n\nTime intelligence functions compare values across time periods:\n\n```\nTotal Sales = SUM(Sales[Amount])\nSales LY = CALCULATE([Total Sales], SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR(Date[Date]))\nSales YTD = TOTALYTD([Total Sales], Date[Date])\nSales QTD = TOTALQTD([Total Sales], Date[Date])\nSales MTD = TOTALMTD([Total Sales], Date[Date])\nMoM Growth = VAR PrevMonth = CALCULATE([Total Sales], PREVIOUSMONTH(Date[Date])) RETURN DIVIDE([Total Sales] - PrevMonth, PrevMonth)\n```\n\n**Key time intelligence functions:**\n- SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR — compare to same period last year\n- PREVIOUSMONTH / PREVIOUSQUARTER / PREVIOUSYEAR — shift time window\n- DATESMTD / DATESQTD / DATESYTD — period-to-date\n- TOTALYTD / TOTALQTD / TOTALMTD — running totals\n- DATEADD — shift by custom intervals\n\n**PL-300 Tip:** Time intelligence requires a proper date table marked as a date table in the model.\n",
        "quiz": [
          {
            "question": "What is DAX used for?",
            "options": [
              "Cleaning data",
              "Writing formulas in Power BI",
              "Connecting databases",
              "Creating charts"
            ],
            "correctAnswerIndex": 1
          },
          { "question": "Interview: Explain CALCULATE in DAX to a beginner.", "options": ["CALCULATE adds numbers", "CALCULATE modifies the filter context of a calculation — it lets you say 'sum sales, but only for this specific condition'", "CALCULATE deletes data", "CALCULATE creates charts"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: What is filter context in DAX and why does it matter?", "options": ["It's a way to filter emails", "Filter context is the set of filters automatically applied when a measure is evaluated — it's why the same measure returns different values on different rows", "It filters out errors", "It's only for dates"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: Write a DAX measure that calculates total sales for the current year only.", "options": ["SUM(Sales[Amount]) AND YEAR=TODAY()", "CALCULATE(SUM(Sales[Amount]), YEAR(Sales[Date]) = YEAR(TODAY()))", "TOTALYTD(SUM(Sales[Amount]), Sales[Date])", "Both B and C are valid approaches"], "correctAnswerIndex": 3 },
          { "question": "Interview: What's the difference between SUM and SUMX in DAX?", "options": ["They are identical", "SUM adds a single column's values, SUMX iterates row-by-row over a table and evaluates an expression for each row before summing", "SUMX is a text function", "SUM can only add two numbers"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "w19-d2",
        "title": "Day 2: Calculated Fields",
        "description": "Create aggregated measures for reports",
        "type": "practice",
        "duration": "45-60 mins",
        "content": "**Calculated fields/measures** aggregate data across rows, unlike calculated columns which work row-by-row.\n\n**Key measures every report needs:**\n```\nTotal Revenue = SUM(Sales[Amount])\nTotal Cost = SUM(Sales[Cost])\nProfit = [Total Revenue] - [Total Cost]\nProfit Margin = DIVIDE([Profit], [Total Revenue])\nYoY Growth = CALCULATE([Total Revenue], SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR(Date[Date]))\n```\n\n**Measure vs. column — when to use which:**\n- Need a value per row (e.g., profit per product)? → Calculated column\n- Need an aggregated value (e.g., total profit across all products)? → Measure\n\n**Time intelligence measures** are powerful for business reporting:\n- Total sales this month vs. last month\n- Same period last year comparison\n- Running total YTD (Year to Date)\n\nStart with simple measures and build up to time intelligence.\n\n**PL-300 Exam Tip:** Measures are evaluated in filter context — the same measure returns different values depending on slicers and report filters. This is the #1 concept tested on the exam.\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhat's the difference between a calculated column and a measure?\nA) They're the same thing\nB) Column works per row; measure works on aggregated data\nC) Column is faster\nD) Measure works per row\nCorrect: B\n\n:::checkpoint\n(PL-300 Style) Why would a measure return different values on two pages of the same report?\nA) The measure is broken\nB) Each page has a different filter context (slicers, page filters)\nC) Measures are random by design\nD) Power BI has a bug\nCorrect: B\n\n## Tableau LOD Expressions (Tableau Desktop Specialist)\n\n**LOD (Level of Detail)** expressions let you compute values at different granularities than the view's level.\n\n**Syntax:**\n```\n{FIXED [Dimension] : AGGR(Measure)}\n{INCLUDE [Dimension] : AGGR(Measure)}\n{EXCLUDE [Dimension] : AGGR(Measure)}\n```\n\n**Examples:**\n- `{FIXED [Category] : SUM(Sales)}` — total sales per category (ignores all other dimensions)\n- `{FIXED [CustomerID] : AVG(Profit)}` — average profit per customer\n- `{EXCLUDE [Region] : SUM(Sales)}` — total sales ignoring region filter\n\n**When to use LOD:**\n- Percent of total by a dimension\n- Customer-level metrics (avg order value per customer)\n- Comparing row-level values to overall averages\n- Removing dimension filters selectively\n\n**PL-300 equivalent:** CALCULATE with REMOVEFILTERS or ALL — same concept of changing filter context.\n",
        "quiz": [
          {
            "question": "Column vs measure difference?",
            "options": [
              "Same",
              "Column per row, measure on aggregates",
              "Column faster",
              "Measure per row"
            ],
            "correctAnswerIndex": 1
          },
          { "question": "Interview: What's the difference between a calculated column and a measure in Power BI?", "options": ["They are the same thing", "A calculated column evaluates row-by-row and stores values in memory, while a measure is evaluated at query time based on filter context", "Measures are slower", "Calculated columns don't use RAM"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: Write a measure for profit margin that safely handles division by zero.", "options": ["Profit / Revenue", "DIVIDE(SUM(Profit), SUM(Revenue)) — DIVIDE handles division by zero gracefully", "IF(Revenue=0,0,Profit/Revenue)", "Profit Margin = SUM(Profit) / SUM(Revenue)"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: In Tableau, what are LOD expressions and when would you use FIXED?", "options": ["LOD stands for Level of Detail", "FIXED computes a value at a specified dimension level regardless of the view's granularity, like calculating total sales per customer even when the view is by product", "LOD expressions are only for maps", "FIXED is the same as EXCLUDE"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: Why might a measure return different values on different pages of the same report?", "options": ["The measure is broken", "Each page has different filter context from slicers, page filters, or visual interactions", "Measures are random", "Power BI has a bug"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "w19-d3",
        "title": "Day 3: Interactive Filters",
        "description": "Add slicers and cross-filtering to dashboards",
        "type": "learn",
        "duration": "45-60 mins",
        "content": "**Filters and slicers** let users interact with dashboards — filtering data to explore specific segments.\n\n**Slicers** — visual filter controls on the report canvas:\n- Dropdown slicer — select from a list\n- Date slicer — choose a date range\n- Timeline slicer — brush across time\n\n**Page-level and report-level filters:**\n- Page filter — applies to one page only\n- Report filter — applies to all pages\n- Drill-through — click a data point to see detailed view\n\n**Cross-filtering:**\nClick a bar in Chart A and Chart B automatically updates to show only that segment's data.\n\n**Best practice:**\n- Put the most important filters as slicers at the top\n- Use clear labels\n- Let users explore without breaking the layout\n\nInteractive filters turn a static report into a data exploration tool.\n\n**Tableau Desktop Specialist Tip:** In Tableau, filters execute in a specific order: Extract Filters → Data Source Filters → Context Filters → Dimension Filters → Measure Filters → Table Calc Filters. Understanding this order is critical for the certification exam.\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhat does a slicer do in a BI report?\nA) Adds a new chart\nB) Lets users interactively filter data\nC) Deletes data\nD) Formats the report\nCorrect: B\n\n:::checkpoint\n(Tableau Style) When you set a dimension as a Context Filter in Tableau, what happens?\nA) It runs after all other filters\nB) It creates a temporary table first, improving performance for subsequent filters\nC) It converts the dimension to a measure\nD) It removes the filter entirely\nCorrect: B",
        "quiz": [
          {
            "question": "What does a slicer do?",
            "options": [
              "Adds chart",
              "Lets users filter data interactively",
              "Deletes data",
              "Formats report"
            ],
            "correctAnswerIndex": 1
          },
          { "question": "Interview: What is cross-filtering and why is it important for dashboards?", "options": ["It filters out bad data", "Cross-filtering lets clicking a chart element filter other charts on the page, creating an interactive exploration experience", "It crosses out data", "It's a type of security filter"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: When would you use a page-level filter vs a report-level filter?", "options": ["They are the same", "Page-level filters apply to one page when different pages need different contexts, report-level filters apply globally to all pages", "Report-level filters don't exist", "Page-level filters are always better"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: How do you design slicers so users don't get confused?", "options": ["Use as many slicers as possible", "Place key slicers at the top, use clear labels, limit to 3-5, and group related slicers together", "Hide slicers in a menu", "Use dropdown style only"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: Explain the filter execution order in Tableau.", "options": ["Filters run in random order", "Extract filters -> Data source filters -> Context filters -> Dimension filters -> Measure filters -> Table calc filters", "Dimension filters run first always", "There is no specific order"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "w19-d4",
        "title": "Day 4: Visual Best Practices",
        "description": "Design clean, accessible, effective dashboards",
        "type": "practice",
        "duration": "45-60 mins",
        "content": "**Visual best practices** — the difference between a dashboard that's useful and one that's confusing.\n\n**1. Choose the right chart:**\n- Trends over time → line chart\n- Category comparison → bar chart\n- Part of a whole → donut/treemap (but use sparingly)\n- Distribution → histogram/boxplot\n- Relationship → scatter plot\n\n**2. Less is more:**\n- Remove gridlines, borders, legends if not essential\n- Use color to highlight, not decorate\n- 3-5 colors max per dashboard\n\n**3. Design principles:**\n- Most important metric top-left (reading order)\n- Consistent fonts and colors\n- White space is not wasted space\n- Mobile-first or screen-size aware\n\n**4. Accessibility:**\n- Colorblind-friendly palettes (avoid red/green alone)\n- Clear labels and tooltips\n- Adequate font sizes\n\nGood design makes insights obvious at a glance.\n\n:::checkpoint\nHow many colors should a typical dashboard use?\nA) As many as possible\nB) 3-5 maximum, used intentionally\nC) Exactly 2\nD) At least 10\nCorrect: B\n\n## Tableau Groups, Sets, and Parameters (Tableau Desktop Specialist)\n\n**Groups** combine dimension members into higher-level categories:\n- Example: group 'Small', 'Medium', 'Large' products into a 'Size' group\n- Right-click a dimension → Create Group\n\n**Sets** are custom subsets of data based on conditions:\n- **Dynamic sets** — update based on conditions (Top 10 products by sales)\n- **Fixed sets** — manually selected members\n- Used in filters, calculations, and as dimensions\n\n**Parameters** are user-input controls (dropdowns, sliders) that drive calculations:\n- Example: parameter to select Top N customers\n- Create a parameter, then use it in a calculated field or filter\n\n**Impact on visual best practices:**\n- Groups simplify cluttered charts (combine 50 products into 5 categories)\n- Sets enable focused analysis (compare Top 10 vs Rest)\n- Parameters make dashboards interactive without needing multiple sheets\n\n**Tableau Desktop Specialist Tip:** Know the difference between groups (combine members) and sets (custom subsets), and how parameters interact with calculated fields.\n",
        "quiz": [
          {
            "question": "How many colors for a dashboard?",
            "options": [
              "As many as possible",
              "3-5 used intentionally",
              "Exactly 2",
              "At least 10"
            ],
            "correctAnswerIndex": 1
          },
          { "question": "Interview: How many colors should a dashboard use and why?", "options": ["As many as available", "3-5 colors max — too many colors overwhelm viewers and dilute the importance of highlighted data", "Exactly 1", "At least 10 for variety"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: What is the difference between a group and a set in Tableau?", "options": ["They are the same", "Groups combine dimension members into higher-level categories, sets are custom subsets of data based on conditions", "Sets combine categories, groups create subsets", "Groups are only for dates"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: How do you make a dashboard accessible to colorblind users?", "options": ["Use only grayscale", "Use colorblind-friendly palettes, add patterns/labels, and avoid red-green combinations for meaning", "Colorblind users can't use dashboards", "Use bright colors only"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 },
          { "question": "Interview: What's the most common dashboard design mistake and how do you avoid it?", "options": ["Using too few charts", "Trying to show everything on one page — focus on one key question per dashboard", "Using too much white space", "Making it too simple"], "correctAnswerIndex": 1 }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "w19-d5",
        "title": "Day 5: Mini-Project: Interactive Dashboard",
        "description": "Build an interactive BI dashboard with measures",
        "type": "project",
        "duration": "1-2 hrs",
        "content": "Build an interactive dashboard:\n\n1. **Connect to or create data** — sales data with date, product, region, amount\n2. **Create 3 measures** — Total Sales, Average Sale, and Profit Margin\n3. **Build 3 visualizations** — sales over time (line), sales by product (bar), sales by region (map or bar)\n4. **Add slicers** — date range and product category\n5. **Apply design best practices** — consistent colors, clear labels, remove clutter\n6. **Test cross-filtering** — clicking one chart updates the others\n\nPublish or export your dashboard.\n\n:::checkpoint\nWhat should you test before sharing a dashboard?\nA) Cross-filtering — do interactions work correctly?\nB) That all colors are different\nC) That it has at least 10 charts\nD) That no filters are available\nCorrect: A",
